The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, March 27, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 Escorts Ltd, a tractor maker, has extended its tie-up with State Bank of India for tractor financing to all states. The scheme was available in four states  Punjab, Haryana, Himachal Pradesh and Jammu and Kashmir, but it has now been extended to cover the whole country.																								 ABN Amro Bank has introduced World Citizen Banking, an initiative for non-resident Indians, in Singapore. The Dutch bank will offer comprehensive banking and investment advisory services to non-resident Indians based in Singapore and South East Asia.																								 Forbes Marshall, specialists in process efficiency and energy conservation, has bagged an order worth Rs 3.95 crore to supply safety relief valves to the Kaiga unit in Karnataka and RAPP in Rajasthan for Nuclear Power Corporation of India Ltd.																								 Bank of Baroda has tied up with Punjab Tractors Ltd to finance tractors to farmers. Under the scheme, farmers will get a special discount of Rs 4,000 and eight free services.																								 Alcatel, a French telecom major, has entered into an agreement with state-owned ITI for DSL deployment in India. ITI chairman Y. K. Pandey said the pact would involve royalty payments which would be finalised later. 																								 Grover Vineyards has received the Agriculture and Processed Food Products Export award for 200 in recognition of its services in promoting export of agricultural products.																								 Tata Steel has won awards for its foray into communication technologies like audio-visuals, intranet sites, websites and e-communication platforms from the Association of Annual Business Communicators of India.																								 Fitch Ratings India has revised the outlook on the fixed deposit rating of Nicco Uco Alliance Credit to negative from stable.																								 Reliance Infocomm has launched a multiplayer game suite on R-World services available for RIM customers. Multiple RIM users can now play games with each other anywhere across India.  ADVERTISEMENT
